<%
  models = begin
    ApplicationRecord.descendants
  rescue => exception
    []
  end
%>
<div>
  <h3>Resources</h3>

  <div>The primary goal of Jav is to administer your database records. To do that Jav, uses the concept of a <strong>Resource</strong>. Each Jav <strong>Resource</strong> corresponds to a <strong>Rails Model</strong>.</div>

  <% if models.present? %>
    <div class="mt-2" data-controller="hidden-input">
      It seems you already have <%= models.count %> <%= 'model'.pluralize models.count %> in your app. You can generate resources for each one with the following commands.

      <strong class="cursor-pointer block mt-2" data-action="click->hidden-input#showContent">Generate resources ðŸ‘‡ (click to reveal)</strong>

      <div class="mt-2 hidden" data-hidden-input-target="content">
        <% models.each do |model| %>
          <code class="text-lg"><%= model.to_s %></code>
          <div>
            <code class="p-1 rounded-sm bg-sky-500 text-white">bin/rails generate jav:resource <%= model.to_s %></code>
          </div>
        <% end %>
      </div>
    </div>
  <% else %>
    <div class="mt-2" data-controller="hidden-input">
      You may generate a resource using the following command:
      <br>

      <code class="p-1 rounded-sm bg-sky-500 text-white">bin/rails generate jav:resource post</code>
    </div>
  <% end %>

  <p>
    <a href="https://docs.javhq.io/2.0/resources.html" target="_blank" title="Jav Resources documentation">Docs</a>
  </p>
</div>

